  "enhanced_information": "In Diabetes Insipidus (DI), there is a deficiency of antidiuretic hormone (ADH), leading to impaired water reabsorption in the kidneys. This results in the production of dilute urine, characterized by low urine osmolality. The standard consensus indicates that urine osmolality in DI is typically less than 300 mmol/L, often around 100-200 mmol/L, reflecting the inability to concentrate urine. Therefore, the most accurate option is <300 mmol/L. The evidence paths regarding the association of DI with the human AVP protein (arginine vasopressin) support the understanding of the hormonal deficiency involved in DI, but they do not directly alter the consensus on urine osmolality."
